## Migration Analysis

Your code has three patterns that break on .NET 8 (`Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`):

| API Found | Location | Pattern |
|-----------|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Exception as control flow |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue after abort |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work â€” same logic that was in the
                // ThreadAbortException catch block
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop; replaces Thread.ResetAbort + _running=false
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals the token â€” replaces Thread.Abort

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation
            // this means GetNextItem or ProcessItem is ignoring the token.
            // Log a warning â€” there is no safe forced-kill equivalent.
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` + `CancellationToken` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool can't wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of preemptive kill |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` guard prevents catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `break` | You control the loop â€” just exit it |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2000)` | `Join` actually waits for the thread; `Sleep` was a blind delay |

## Critical Pitfall: The Blocking `GetNextItem` Call

The original `GetNextItem()` "may block" per your comment. **This is the hardest part.** A `CancellationToken` can't interrupt code that doesn't check it. You must modify `GetNextItem` to accept and honor the token:

```csharp
// If it blocks on a queue, use BlockingCollection<T> which supports tokens:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException when cancelled
}

// If it blocks on a WaitHandle (ManualResetEvent, etc.):
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(
        new[] { _dataReady, token.WaitHandle });
    if (index == 1)
        throw new OperationCanceledException(token);
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If it blocks on Thread.Sleep:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(pollIntervalMs); // wakes immediately on cancel
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

If `GetNextItem` calls third-party code you **cannot modify**, move it to a child process and use `Process.Kill` as the last resort.

## Dispose Pattern

`CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable` â€” leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The migrated class implements `IDisposable` and disposes the CTS in `Dispose()`.
